        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Royal Gardens Kew</hi></placeName>
                    <date>October 7/72 </date>
                    <salute>Dear Darwin</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>Your groom informed me that Parslow often knew of a horse to be bought—<ref target="#foot.f1"/> Would you let me ask him or will you if he is with you, whether he knows of any thing that would meet the enclosed conditions</p>
<p>The Droseras arrived, but I am sorry to say knocked to pieces, the soil not having been secured— It is a matter of no moment— we shall bring them round or kill them—which latter we should probably have done ere this had they not gone to you.<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>I am distressed to hear of your bad health &amp; move to Seven Oaks—<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>I hope that you will see the lovely place that Spottiswoode has taken.<ref target="#foot.f4"/></p>
<p>What do you think of Mallette’s Earthquaque theory— Will it not account for the strata dipping inwards at the base of ranges of mountains?<ref target="#foot.f5"/></p>
<p>All quiet here at present | Ever yours affec | J D Hooker</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
        <div type="enclosure" subtype="other" xml:id="encl.1">
      
          <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>Wanted a Nag (<hi rend="underline">not a Filly</hi>) for Cart &amp; throwing machine—say 6 years old—15-2 to 16 hands high—clean legs—good action—Sound &amp; quiet in harness &amp; chains.</p>
<p>Blindness no objection.</p>
<p>Price £40. 0. 0.</p>
<p>Two <hi rend="underline">may</hi> be wanted. If Mr Parslow should hear of any to let D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Hooker know when &amp; where it may be seen.</p> 
                </div>
        
    </div>

            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">CD’s groom was <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_5436.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Mark Ansell</ref>; <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_3699.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Joseph Parslow</ref> was his butler.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-8542.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to J. D. Hooker, 4 October [1872]</ref> and n. 2.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-8542.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to J. D. Hooker, 4 October [1872]</ref> and n. 5.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4500.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">William Spottiswoode</ref> bought Combe Bank, a house in Sundridge, a village near Sevenoaks, Kent, in December 1871 (<hi rend="italic">London Gazette</hi>, 29 December 1871, pp. 5893–4).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_3147.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Robert Mallet’s</ref> paper on volcanic energy was read in June 1872 (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_5176.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Mallet 1872</ref>). Mallet noted that earthquakes occurred ‘within the area of great seismic bands which follow and extend at either side of the mountain-chains of the world’ (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_5176.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Mallet 1872</ref>, p. 148; for more on Mallet’s theory of the dynamics of earthquakes, see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1901.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Dean 1991</ref>). CD had theorised about the action of earthquakes and the elevation of mountain chains in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_8002.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">‘Volcanic phenomena and the formation of mountain chains’</ref>.</note>
        </div>        
            
